#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:2
msgid "Aggregating activities of several aliquots"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:4
msgid ""
"In certain cases, the measurement of a sample activity requires to "
"determine the output quantity value from several compartments of the "
"sample, or, regarding a surface contamination, from several measurements "
"covering the entire surface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:9
msgid ""
"This chapter describes how to proceed if several activity measurements, "
"also of different types of measurements, need to be aggregated to obtain "
"a single output quantity value. This value may be calculated as a sum or "
"as an average of the single values. The simple aggregation method as "
"described below also includes the calculation of the associated decision "
"threshold and the detection limit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:16
msgid ""
"If these measurements, however, represent repeated measurements in order "
"to obtain a series of measurement values for a single input quantity, the"
" recommended methods would be those described in section :ref:`using data"
" sets for mean and variance` and :ref:`Gross quantity: Variance "
"interpolation for a mean`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:22
msgid "**Activating the evaluation of several aliquot measurements**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:24
msgid ""
"In the text field for equations, the following call is inserted for "
"defining the activity as an aggregation of several values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:27
msgid "*Asum = SumEval(mode, np, A1, A2, …)*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:29
msgid ""
"The name of the symbol to the left of the = sign may be freely chosen. "
"The name **SumEval** represents the internal procedure which does the "
"calculations necessary for the aggregation of measured aliquot values. "
"Its arguments are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:34
msgid "*mode* integer number, withe values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:36
msgid "1: calculate the mean value of the individual results,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:38
msgid "2: calculate the sum of the individual results,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:40
msgid "*np* integer, number of aliquot measurements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:42
msgid ""
"*A1, A2, …* the list *np* of symbol names (freely chosen) representing "
"the activity or activity concentration values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:45
msgid ""
"Directly following the SumEval call, at first those main equations for "
"calculating the activities Ai are inserted,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:48
msgid "Ai = wi \\* Rneti , for i=1 to np, one after another"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:50
msgid ""
"These are followed by the lists of equations defining the calibration "
"factors wi and the net count rates Rneti:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:53
msgid "Rneti = Rbi – R0i"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:55
msgid ""
"It is recommended to use further equations for explaining the count rates"
" by their associated numbers of counts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:58
msgid "A complete example for two aliquot measurements may be defined as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:61
msgid "*a = 1/F \\* Asum*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:63
msgid "*Asum = SumEval(1, 2, A1, A2)*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:65
msgid "*A1 = w1 \\* Rnet1*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:67
msgid "*A2 = w2 \\* Rnet2*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:69
msgid "*W1 = 1/eps1*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:71
msgid "*W2 = 1/eps2*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:73
msgid "*Rnet1 = Rb1 – R0*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:75
msgid "*Rnet2 = Rb2 – R0*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:77
msgid "*Rb1 = Nb1 / tb*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:79
msgid "*Rb2 = Nb2 / tb*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:81
msgid "*R0 = N0 / t0*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:83
msgid ""
"Such factors found in all expressions of wi, may be extracted from the "
"wi, i.e., not included in SumEval, as for instance the factor 1/F (1 / "
"surface area) in the equation above that declaring Asum. This helps "
"preventing covariances between the wi. An input quantity being part of "
"several equations generates covariances between the quantities defined by"
" these equations. This is true for the count rate R0 in the example given"
" above, introducing a covariance between Rnet1 und Rnet2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:91
msgid ""
"Such covariances, however, need not be identified explicitly by the user."
" They are considered by the uncertainty propagation applied within the "
"*SumEval* procedure in the way, that covariance contributions of the form"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:96
msgid ""
"u\\left( x_{a,i},x_{a,j} \\right) = \\sum_{k}^{}{\\frac{\\partial "
"x_{a,i}}{\\partial x_{u,k}}\\frac{\\partial x_{a,j}}{\\partial "
"x_{u,k}}u^{2}\\left( x_{u,k} \\right)}\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:98
msgid ""
"induced by the independent input quantities :math:`x_{u,k}` between "
"dependent quantities :math:`x_{a,i}`, are taken into account; refer to "
":numref:`uncertainty propagation`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:102
msgid "**Note**: This procedure does not require further windows dialogs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:104
msgid "**Notes about calculating the decision threshold and the detection limit**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:107
msgid ""
"Calculations of the decision threshold and especially the detection limit"
" require to vary the value :math:`a` of the output quantity. Such an "
"iteration step generates a modified value, denoted as :math:`a'`. This "
"has to be transformed to new values :math:`A_{i}^{'}` of the individual "
"values :math:`A_{i}` as part of *SumEval.* Two possible ways may be "
"applied, which, based on the sample equations given above, are explained "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:115
msgid ""
"If a mean value is to be calculated from the :math:`A_{i}`, a meaningful "
"option would be to set all :math:`A_{i}^{'}` to the same value "
":math:`a'`. The least-squares method is used as indicated in `section "
"7.14 <#least-squares-calculation-of-a-weighted-mean-and-its-standard-"
"uncertainty>`__ for calculating a weighed mean."
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:121
msgid ""
"If instead a sum of aliquot values is to be derived, it may be "
"meaningful, to modify the values :math:`A_{i}^{'}` such that the original"
" ratios between the :math:`A_{i}` values are maintained. This may be "
"achieved by applying relative “form“ factors :math:`h_{i}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:126
msgid ":math:`h_{i} = \\frac{A_{i}}{a = \\sum_{j = 1}^{np}A_{j}}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:128
msgid "such that"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:130
msgid ":math:`{A_{i} = h}_{i}a`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:132
msgid ""
"Then, the modified values :math:`A_{i}^{'}` – and thereby the gross count"
" rates :math:`R_{b,i}^{'}` – are internally calculated from :math:`a'`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:136
msgid ":math:`Asum^{'} = a^{'}\\ F`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:138
msgid ":math:`R_{net,i}^{'} = \\frac{Asum^{'} \\bullet h_{i}}{w_{i}}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:140
msgid ":math:`R_{b,i}^{'} = \\frac{Asum^{'} \\bullet h_{i}}{w_{i}} + R_{0}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:142
msgid ""
":math:`N_{b,i}^{'} = \\left( \\frac{Asum^{'} \\bullet h_{i}}{w_{i}} + "
"R_{0} \\right)\\ t_{m}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:144
msgid ""
"The associated uncertainties then are, again referring to the complete "
"example given above:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:147
msgid ":math:`u\\left( N_{b,i}^{'} \\right) = \\sqrt{N_{b,i}^{'}}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:149
msgid ":math:`u\\left( R_{b,i}^{'} \\right) = \\sqrt{R_{b,i}^{'}/t_{m}}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:151
msgid ""
":math:`u\\left( R_{n,i}^{'} \\right) = \\sqrt{R_{b,i}^{'}/t_{m} + "
"R_{0}/t_{0}}`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../doc_files/special_methods/aggregating_acctivities.rst:153
msgid ""
"From the uncertainties of the modified gross count rates, the uncertainty"
" :math:`u(a^{'})` associated with the activity value :math:`a'` is "
"calculated. Such pairs :math:`(a^{'},\\ u(a^{'}))` are used for the "
"iteration necessary for the detection limit calculation."
msgstr ""

